{"parse":{"title":"Michelle Delio","pageid":1869339,"revid":851348977,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Michelle Delio</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Freelance_writer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Freelance writer\">freelance writer</a> whose articles have appeared in <a href=\"/wiki/Wired_News\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wired News\">Wired News</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/InfoWorld\" title=\"InfoWorld\">InfoWorld</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Technology_Review\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Technology Review\">MIT Technology Review</a>. She has also written under her maiden name 'Michelle Finley'.\n</p><p>In 2005, it was alleged that Delio had made up 'color quotes' for some of her articles. The incident began when Delio published an article at <a href=\"/wiki/Technology_Review\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Technology Review\">MIT Technology Review</a> based on an interview with 'G.S', an anonymous insider at <a href=\"/wiki/Hewlett-Packard\" title=\"Hewlett-Packard\">Hewlett-Packard</a> who claimed the existence of a misogynistic attitude at the company towards then-CEO <a href=\"/wiki/Carly_Fiorina\" title=\"Carly Fiorina\">Carly Fiorina</a> and female staff in general.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>After <a href=\"/wiki/Hewlett-Packard\" title=\"Hewlett-Packard\">Hewlett-Packard</a> challenged the author's sources, MIT Technology Review retracted the article. <a href=\"/wiki/Wired_News\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wired News\">Wired News</a> conducted an internal study, which determined that a number of Delio's 'secondary' sources (i.e., those added for color or supporting quotes) were unverifiable,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> but that her 'primary' sources (i.e., those most essential to her stories) were legitimate. Of 160 stories reviewed, 24 had problems with at least one source, although no evidence was forthcoming to suggest the main substance of the articles was skewed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Wired News amended 24 of Delio's articles, while MIT Technology Review retracted 10 completely.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Michelle_Delio&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.technologyreview.com/view/404075/did-michelle-delio-fabricate-sources/\">http://www.technologyreview.com/view/404075/did-michelle-delio-fabricate-sources/</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.wired.com/2002/11/mitnicks-lost-chapter-found/\">Reader's advisory: Wired News has been unable to confirm some sources for a number of stories written by this author. If you have any information about sources cited in this article, please send an e-mail to sourceinfo(AT)wired.com.\"</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.wired.com/images/pdf/penenberg_report.pdf\">https://www.wired.com/images/pdf/penenberg_report.pdf</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.gelfmagazine.com/archives/what_we_can_learn_from_michelle_delio.php\">http://www.gelfmagazine.com/archives/what_we_can_learn_from_michelle_delio.php</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2005/05/67428\">https://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2005/05/67428</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://slashdot.org/articles/05/05/10/1827221.shtml\">http://slashdot.org/articles/05/05/10/1827221.shtml</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Flag_of_the_United_States.svg\" class=\"image\" title=\"United States\"><img alt=\"Stub icon 1\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/25px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png\" width=\"25\" height=\"13\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/38px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/50px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1235\" data-file-height=\"650\" /></a> <a href=\"/wiki/File:Crystal_personal.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon 2\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/24/Crystal_personal.svg/20px-Crystal_personal.svg.png\" width=